## Model of Computation: Word-RAM

This part was confusing at first, but I understand it like this:

The Word-RAM model is a simplified computer model used to analyze algorithms.

It assumes the computer has:

- Memory
- A processor
- Fixed-size machine words
- Basic operations that take constant time

A machine word is a fixed-size block of bits, like 32 bits or 64 bits.

In this model, we assume these operations take `O(1)` time:

- Adding numbers
- Subtracting numbers
- Comparing numbers
- Reading from memory
- Writing to memory

This does not mean real computers are always this simple. It is just a model that helps us analyze algorithms in a clean way.

The main idea:

> Word-RAM is the “fake simple computer” we use so we can talk about algorithm performance without worrying about every hardware detail.

---

## Data Structure

A data structure is a way to store data and support operations on that data.

Examples:

- Array
- Linked list
- Hash table
- Tree
- Heap

The same data can be stored in different ways, and each way has different performance.

For example, if I store students in an array, checking whether a birthday already exists may require searching through many previous students.

But if I store birthdays in a hash table, checking whether a birthday exists can be much faster.

So choosing the right data structure can make an algorithm much faster.

---

## Interface

An interface is the set of operations that a data structure supports.

For example, a sequence interface may support:

- Get item at index
- Set item at index
- Insert item
- Delete item

A set interface may support:

- Add item
- Remove item
- Check if item exists

The important idea is:

> Interface is what we can do. Data structure is how it is implemented.

Different data structures can support the same interface but with different runtimes.

---

## Static Array

A static array has:

- Fixed size
- Fixed-width slots
- Fast access by index

Operations:

- Create array of size `n`: `Θ(n)`
- Get item at index `i`: `Θ(1)`
- Set item at index `i`: `Θ(1)`

So arrays are good when I need fast access by index.

But they are not always good for searching unless the data is organized in a helpful way.

---

## Birthday Match Code

The lecture uses this example:

```python
def birthday_match(students):
    n = len(students)
    record = StaticArray(n)

    for k in range(n):
        (name1, bday1) = students[k]

        for i in range(k):
            (name2, bday2) = record.get_at(i)

            if bday1 == bday2:
                return (name1, name2)

        record.set_at(k, (name1, bday1))

    return None
```

The outer loop runs `n` times.

The inner loop runs:

- 0 times for the first student
- 1 time for the second student
- 2 times for the third student
- ...
- `n - 1` times for the last student

So the total work is roughly:

```text
0 + 1 + 2 + ... + (n - 1)
```

That becomes `O(n²)`.

So this version works, but it is not the best possible version.

